hese hitherto invisible practices were an integral part of the social dynamic of the conflict and had important implications for the broader organization of nationalist forms of resistance and gender relationships. Combining interpretative anthropology and poststructuralist feminist theory, Aretxaga contributes not only to anthropology and feminist studies but also to research on ethnic and social conflict by showing the gendered constitution of political violence. She goes further than asserting that violence affects men and women differently by arguing that the manners in which violence is gendered are not fixed but constantly shifting, depending on the contingencies of history, social class, and ethnic identity. Thus any attempt at subverting gender inequality is necessarily colored by other dimensions of political experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNationalismzNorthern Ireland. 0aWomen political activistszNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzNorthern IrelandzBelfast. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aArnold, Matthew.  aBeechmount.  aBeresford, David.  aBurton, Frank.  aCallaghan, Rosemary (Rosie).  aCivil Rights Movement.  aClonard.  aCornell, Drucilla.  aCuchulain.  aDarby, John.  aEaster 1916.  aEvason, Eileen.  aFarrell, Mairead.  aFeldman, Allen.  aFernandez, James.  aFoucault, Michel.  aGaelic Brehon Law.  aHeaney, Seamus.  aIndia.  aJones, Emrys.  aKristeva, Julia.  aLong Kesh.  aMani, Lata.  aMcCafferty, Nell.  aO'Malley, Padraig.  aRenan, Ernest.  aabortion.  adirty protest.  adispossession.  adivorce.  ahouse searches.  ajudiciary.  alandscape.  ametonymy.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978